for_each meta argument : 
a more flexible way to manage multiple resources
-pulls values from a MAP or SET rather than from a NUMBER.
-rather than an index, resources gets a unique key as a reference, make it more stable than count
-ideal for managing unique config : use it when resources need different names, tags, or settings

REFACTORING TERRAFORM STATE: 
Reorganising how terraform tracks your infrastructure without changing the infrastructure itself.

Common scenarios : 
-  you renamed a resource in your code
-  you are reorganising modules
-  you need to adopt existing infrastructure
-  you want to stop managing something but keep it running
without refactoring terraform thinks you are destroying the old resources & creating new ones

The NEW way : 
- Use configuration blocks : moved , removed , import
- Declared your .tf files
- Version controlled alongside your infrastructure
- Reviewable in PRs
- Part of the standard plan/apply workflow
- can be tested before being applied


MOVING RESOURCES WITH THE MOVED BLOCK : 
When we try to rename the vpc or any other resource terraform will destroy it and create new one. Thats where we need moved block.

Two parameters :
-from : specify the orignal resource addr
-to : specify the new resource addr

State updates only : 
-updates only the state file- no infra changes are made

Resource blocks must exist : 
-You must write the new resource blocks before refactoring resource addr.
moved {
  from = aws_instance.server
  to = aws_instance.web_server
}
moved {
  from = aws_s3_bucket.data
  to  = module.storage.aws_s3_bucket.data
}

The refactoring workflow : 
write: add new resource blocks to terraform config.
write : add new moved blocks to terraform config.
plan : terraform plan
apply : terraform apply
delete : delete moved blocks    //not needed after refactor

REMOVING RESOURCES WITH THE REMOVED BLOCK :
REMOVED block instructs terraform to remove a resource from state.

Lifecycle argument: destroy = false
by default, terraform removes the resource from state and destroys the actual resource.

State removal only : 
Removes from state file - infrastructure remains untouched
you must also remove the resource block from your config.

removed {
 from = google_sql_database_instance.prd_db_1
 lifecycle {
   destroy = false
 }
}



















